# TEST CASES FOLDER STRUCTURE [MANDATORY]

## Rule: Test cases MUST use a flat single-file layout under `Cursor-Project/test_cases/`

When creating, moving, or organizing test cases, ALWAYS follow this structure. This is the only accepted layout for test case files.

---

## Root layout (flat — one `.md` per topic)

**Path:** `Cursor-Project/test_cases/`

All test case files live **directly** under the root — no sub-folders (no `Objects/`, no `Flows/`).

**Path pattern:** `test_cases/<Topic_name>.md`

- **&lt;Topic_name&gt;** = descriptive name for the task, bug, feature, or flow being tested. Use underscores for multi-word names.
- One `.md` file per topic. All test cases (backend and frontend) for that topic are inside the single file.

**Examples:**
- `test_cases/Invoice_cancellation.md`
- `test_cases/Product_contract_create.md`
- `test_cases/Contract_termination.md`
- `test_cases/POD_coordinate_search.md`
- `test_cases/Billing_credit_note_reversal.md`

---

## README (index of all test case files)

- **test_cases/README.md** — Lists every test case file with a short description (topic, Jira key if applicable). Update this README whenever a new test case file is added.

No sub-folder READMEs are needed (there are no sub-folders).

---

## Internal structure of each test case file (Backend / Frontend split)

Every test case `.md` file MUST be divided into two main sections: **Backend Test Cases** and **Frontend Test Cases**. Each section has its own numbered test cases.

### TC numbering

- **Backend:** `TC-BE-1`, `TC-BE-2`, `TC-BE-3`, …
- **Frontend:** `TC-FE-1`, `TC-FE-2`, `TC-FE-3`, …

Each TC heading includes its type: `TC-BE-1 (Positive): {title}` or `TC-FE-2 (Negative): {title}`.

### Mandatory coverage per section

- Each section (Backend and Frontend) MUST include at least one **(Positive)** and one **(Negative)** test case.
- If a topic genuinely has no backend or no frontend test cases, the section heading MUST still be present with a note: *"No backend test cases applicable for this scope."* or *"No frontend test cases applicable for this scope."*

### File skeleton

```
# {Document title} – {Short scope} ({JIRA_KEY})

**Jira:** …  **Type:** …  **Summary:** …
**Scope:** …

---

## Test data (preconditions)
{Shared setup — environment, entities, data chain}

---

## Backend Test Cases

### TC-BE-1 (Positive): {title}
**Description:** … **Preconditions:** … **Test steps:** … **Expected test case results:** …

### TC-BE-2 (Negative): {title}
…

---

## Frontend Test Cases

### TC-FE-1 (Positive): {title}
**Description:** … **Preconditions:** … **Test steps:** … **Expected test case results:** …

### TC-FE-2 (Negative): {title}
…

---

## References
```

---

## Content of test case files (structure and readability)

The **content** of each test case `.md` file MUST follow the **Test Case Template**: **`Cursor-Project/config/template/Test_case_template.md`**. That template defines: document header (title, Jira, Type, Summary, Scope), Test data (preconditions), then Backend and Frontend sections with TC-BE-N / TC-FE-N scenarios. Each scenario has: Test title (in the TC heading), Description, Preconditions, Test steps, Expected test case results, Actual result (if bug), References. Test cases must be **maximally detailed** and **human-readable** (plain English, full sentences where helpful, no unexplained jargon). See the template for placeholders and examples.

---

## Summary

1. **Root:** `Cursor-Project/test_cases/`
2. **Layout:** Flat — one `.md` file per topic directly under root (no sub-folders).
3. **Naming:** `<Topic_name>.md` with underscores (e.g. `Invoice_cancellation.md`).
4. **Internal split:** Every file has **Backend Test Cases** (`TC-BE-N`) and **Frontend Test Cases** (`TC-FE-N`) sections.
5. **Coverage:** Both sections must have positive + negative TCs (or an explicit N/A note).
6. **README:** Only `test_cases/README.md` — index of all test case files.

Always use this layout when creating or organizing test cases. Violation: place test case files in sub-folders, omit the Backend/Frontend split, or use the old Objects/Flows structure for new test cases.
